@Node Warning "Exec-Handler - WARNING"
@next Features
@prev Main

  This software is intended mainly for developers, who wish to improve
  their development environment a bit. I don't suppose there is any other
  sensitive application for this handler, if there is, let @{"me" link "Author"} know.

  The source file "loadseg.asm" was taken and adapted from the PCMCIA
  example code of the 3.1 Developer Kit distributed by Commodore-Amiga,
  Inc. I don't feel of doing something illegal because this source doesn't
  contain any magic, but is only a better version of the dos.library/-
  InternalLoadSeg() system call.

  This software is freeware. It is provided as-is and is subject to
  change; no warranties are made. All use is at your own risk. No
  liability or responsibility is assumed.

  @{ub}
@EndNode

@Node Features "Exec-Handler - Feaures"
@prev Warning
@next Requirements

  @{b}Features@{ub}

  · Supports any linker that creates the executable in one go
    (i.e. that doesn't Seek())

  · Full blown CLI environment

  · Completely pure code

  · Distributed as Freeware, complete source code is supplied

@EndNode

@Node Requirements "Exec-Handler - Requirements"
@next Motivation
@prev Warning

  @{b}Requirements@{ub}

  This package requires AmigaOS Release 2.04 or higher. However, the
  supplied Installer script assumes an AmigaOS Release 2.1, and tries to
  install a DOSDriver file in EXECS:DOSDrivers.

  I don't suppose that there are potential users out there running 2.0 who
  want to use the Exec-Handler. If I'm wrong, though, it shouldn't be a
  major problem for such people to create a Mountlist entry themselves.

@EndNode


@Node Motivation "Exec-Handler - Motivation"
@next Installation
@prev Requirements

  @{b}Motivation@{ub}

  A major advantage of popular development systems found for example in
  the MS-DOS world is the ability to compile directly to memory. This
  reduces disk access, saves time and is quite user-friendly as well.
  Funny enough, this is very rarely found on the Amiga, which was my
  incentive to fill this gap.

  Further more, playing around with processes is always fun (well, most of
  the time...).

@EndNode

@Node Installation "Exec-Handler - Installation"
@next Usage
@prev Main

  @{b}Installation@{ub}

  It is best to use the supplied installer script in order to install
  the exec-handler properly. If you still want to do the installation
  manually then follow the steps listed below.

  As usual for any AmigaDOS-Handler, the actuall handler code is best
  copied to "L:":

      @{b}AmigaShell> copy exec-handler l:@{ub}

  The mount specification entry may be copied to "EXECS:DOSDrivers" in
  order to have it always mounted during system startup:

      @{b}AmigaShell> copy EXEC EXEC.info EXECS:DOSDrivers@{ub}

  Copy it to "SYS:Storage/DOSDrivers", if you want to use it more rarely:

      @{b}AmigaShell> copy EXEC EXEC.info SYS:Storage/DOSDrivers@{ub}

  This way you will have to mount it manually in order to use it,
  though.

  Note that the EXEC icon has set the tooltype 'ACTIVATE' set to 0, which
  tells AmigaDOS to defer the actual loading of the handler-code until the
  first usage. Therefore you only loose some memory for the
  AmigaDOS-internal representation of the DOS-driver, if you don't use it.

@EndNode

@Node Usage "Exec-Handler - Usage / Stream names"
@next Caveats
@prev Usage

  @{b}Usage and the construction of stream names@{ub}

  When using the exec-handler, you have to construct a so-called
  stream-name which contains all the information needed to access the
  raw exec in question.

  First, a @{"Stream name conversion" link StreamConversion } will be done.

  Next, the following ReadArgs() template is applied the the stream name.

  NAME,S=STACKSIZE/K/N,CWD=CURRENTWORKDIR/K,WIN=WINDOW/K,ARGS=ARGUMENTS/K,
  HOME=HOMEDIR/K,PRI=PRIORITY/K/N"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
     This is an arbitrary string. It is used as the CLI program name as
     you get it via dos.library/GetProgramName().
     Defaults to "Object".

  @{b}STACKSIZE@{ub}
     Size of the stack for the executed program.
     Defaults to 4096 bytes.

  @{b}CURRENTWORKDIR@{ub}
     Current working directory for the executed program.
     Defaults to "".

  @{b}HOMEDIR@{ub}
     PROGDIR: for the executed program.
     Defaults to "".

  @{b}WINDOW@{ub}
     Input and Output console window specification. Syntactically, this
     parameter is treated {"specially" link StreamConversion }.
     Defaults to "CON:0/0/640/150/Output/AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE".

  @{b}PRIORITY@{ub}
     Exec task priority for the executed program.
     Defaults to 0.

  @{b}ARGUMENTS@{ub}
     Arguments for the executed program.
     Defaults to "".

  Some example stream names, which are all valid (but which do not mean
  the same, though)

     EXEC:Job/PRI.1/ARGS.Arg1
     "EXEC:Job/PRI=1/ARGS=*"Arg1 Arg2 Arg3*""

   Please read also the @{"Caveats" link Caveats} section.

@EndNode

@Node Caveats "Exec-Handler - Caveats"
@next Future
@prev Usage

  @{b}Caveats@{ub}

  This section tries to address some known problems.

  I will always try to give the user the necessary technical background to
  understand the problem and, if possible, to include a work-around.

  If any user has found a similar problem which is not mentioned in this
  document, he or she should contact @{"me" link Author} in order to append it to this
  section.

  @{b}exec-handler and overlays@{ub}

     As for this version (and probably all future ones) the exec-handler
     does not support overlaid files.

  @{b}exec-handler and special linkers@{ub}

     During development, I tested the exec-handler with blink/slink. At
     least for small programs this linker seems to write it's output
     in one go, i.e. it does not do any Seek() operation. However, I
     can well imagine that not all linkers are that decent with respect
     to my handler. For this version, the exec-handler does only
     implement a very small set of AmigaDOS packets, particularly @{i} not @{ui}
     including ACTION_SEEK.

@EndNode

